PPL IT is funding projects for 12 months fighting against VAWG.

AA Zim is continuing to deliver programming which encourages the questioning of power imbalances and acceptance of violence against women and girls (VAWG). Activities are taking place in schools and in communities, focused on challenging the root causes of gendered inequalities and VAWG through critically analysing use of power and identifying actions to balance power. In schools a participatory theatre approach (Tuseme) is used and in communities a there is a community mobilisation approach (SASA! Together). SASA! Together is a phased approach that works through stages of change with a whole community (moving through start, awareness, support, and action).  With previous PPL funding the project launched the start phase (direct beneficiary funding). In this second phase the project is moving into the awareness phase.

ActionAid UK has a partnership with People's Postcode Lottery and benefits directly from lottery draws assigned within a calendar year. This will be the final year in which ActionAid UK benefits from these draws, as PPL's funding model changes in 2021. In 2020/21, funds have been assigned to girl-led research and the development of a toolkit for working with adolescent girls. This will bring together learnings from previous PPL-funded projects about what works in supporting adolescent girls, and identify good practices as well as advocacy objectives for this area. AA Zimbabwe has also received funding for continuation of a project amplifying girls' voices, and will integrate a new community-based methodology, SASA! Together, to address VAWG. Innovative humanitarian projects will also receive funding across the ActionAid federation. Part of the funds also go to AAUK for both internal strategic projects and to cover the grant management support provided to implementing countries.
ActionAid Arab Region is conducting a scoping study and pilot project to define engagement in Syria for humanitarian purposes.

ActionAid International Kenya (AAIK) will work towards improving the immediate food security of vulnerable households/people in Baringo County. AAIK will provide urgent food parcel distribution as well as providing one nutritious meal per day in schools. Furthermore AAIK will support drought affected communities to access safe and clean water to reduce incidence of waterborne diseases and improve hygiene and sanitation practices.

ActionAid’s scope of work is to deliver a number of girl-centred, interconnected interventions at different levels of the social ecological model, as per the programme’s Theory of Change: 

At community level: in designated agreed geographies, ActionAid will lead the delivery of a targeted package of interventions at community level to support communities to end the practice, and  build the evidence base towards the programme’s intended results  

At sub-national and national level: to support and strengthen mechanisms to respond to issues of violence and FGM/C as well as support the enabling policy environment through supporting women’s networks, girl and youth led organisations, and holding duty bearers accountable 

Globally: to support the programme’s global communications and advocacy goals through leveraging ActionAid’s work at community level and with its grassroots partners in the end FGM/C movement ,e.g. amplifying activists’ voices, sharing positive stories of change

ActionAid UK has a partnership with People's Postcode Lottery and benefits directly from lottery draws assigned within a calendar year. This year, funds have been assigned to projects focused on empowering adolescent girls in Zimbabwe and Ghana; the Women's Rights Funding Fellowship which is operational in Kenya, Rwanda and Zambia, and innovative humanitarian projects across the ActionAid federation. Part of the funds also go to AAUK for both internal strategic projects and to cover the grant management support provided to implementing countries.

ActionAid UK is piloting a new fellowship, funded by the People's Postcode Lottery, to bring together three ActionAid federation memebrs and their Women's Rights Organisations affiliates to build resource mobilisation and programme management capacity.
